## Code of Conduct

Be respectful, inclusive, and constructive. We welcome contributors of all backgrounds and experience levels. Harassment or discrimination of any kind will not be tolerated.

---

## Getting Started

### Prerequisites

- **Node.js** ≥ 20
- **pnpm** ≥ 9 (`npm install -g pnpm`)
- **Docker Desktop** (for PostgreSQL)
- A `.env` file — copy `.env.example` and fill in the values

### Installation

```bash
# 1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/Rythmons/Rythmons.git
cd Rythmons

# 2. Install dependencies
pnpm install

# 3. Start the database
docker compose up -d

# 4. Run migrations
pnpm db:migrate

# 5. Seed the database with demo data
pnpm db:seed

# 6. Start the dev server
pnpm dev
```

### Demo accounts (after seed)

| Email | Password | Role |
|---|---|---|
| demo.artist@rythmons.local | Rythmons123! | Artist |
| demo.organizer@rythmons.local | Rythmons123! | Organizer |
| demo.both@rythmons.local | Rythmons123! | Both |

---

## Project Structure

This is a **Turborepo** monorepo. The main packages are:

```
apps/
  web/          → Next.js application (App Router)
packages/
  api/          → tRPC routers & server logic
  db/           → Prisma schema & migrations
  validation/   → Zod schemas shared across packages
  auth/         → Better Auth configuration
```

---

## Development Workflow

1. **Fork** the repository and create your branch from `main`
2. Make your changes
3. Run checks before committing:

```bash
pnpm check          # Biome lint + format
pnpm check-types    # TypeScript strict check
```

4. Commit your changes (see [Commit Convention](#commit-convention))
5. Push and open a Pull Request

---

## Branching Strategy

| Branch pattern | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `main` | Stable, production-ready code |
| `feat/short-description` | New features |
| `fix/short-description` | Bug fixes |
| `chore/short-description` | Maintenance, deps updates |
| `docs/short-description` | Documentation only |

Branch names should be lowercase and use hyphens. Example: `feat/booking-calendar`.

---

## Commit Convention

We follow [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/):

```
<type>(optional scope): short description

Examples:
feat(artist): add genre filter to search
fix(venue): correct haversine radius filtering
chore(deps): update @trpc/server to v11
docs: update contributing guide
```

| Type | When to use |
|---|---|
| `feat` | New feature |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `chore` | Build, tooling, dependencies |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `refactor` | Code change without feature/fix |
| `test` | Adding or fixing tests |
| `style` | Formatting, no logic change |

---

## Pull Request Process

- Keep PRs focused — one concern per PR
- Link any related issue in the PR description (`Closes #42`)
- Ensure `pnpm check` and `pnpm check-types` pass before opening
- Add a short description of **what** changed and **why**
- Screenshots or demo clips are welcome for UI changes
- A maintainer will review within a few days

---

## Code Style

This project uses **[Biome](https://biomejs.dev/)** for linting and formatting — no Prettier, no ESLint.

```bash
# Check everything
pnpm check

# Auto-fix formatting
pnpm check --write
```

Key conventions:
- TypeScript strict mode — no `any`, use proper types
- Zod schemas live in `packages/validation`
- Prisma queries go through `ctx.db` (server) or direct `db` import (routers that import directly)
- New columns that may not exist in all environments must go through `getColumnAvailability` in `prisma-compat.ts`

---

## Reporting Bugs

Open an issue using the **Bug Report** template. Please include:

- A clear description of the bug
- Steps to reproduce
- Expected vs actual behaviour
- Environment (OS, Node version, browser if relevant)

---

## Suggesting Features

Open an issue using the **Feature Request** template. Describe:

- The problem you're trying to solve
- Your proposed solution
- Any alternatives you considered

---

## Questions?

Open a **Discussion** on GitHub rather than an issue. We're happy to help!
